# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: supercapacitors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Capacitors and inductors as used in electric circuits are not ideal components with only capacitance or inductance.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Additionally, audio components may report a "Q factor", incorporating ESR among other things, at 1000 Hz.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Electrical circuit theory deals with ideal resistors, capacitors and inductors, each assumed to contribute only resistance, capacitance or inductance to the circuit.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] However, all components have a non-zero value of each of these parameters.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] In particular, all physical devices are constructed of materials with finite electrical resistance, so that physical components have some resistance in addition to their other properties.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] The physical origins of ESR depend on the device in question.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] One way to deal with these inherent resistances in circuit analysis is to use a lumped-element model to express each physical component as a combination of an ideal component and a small resistor in series, the ESR.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] The ESR can be measured and included in a component's datasheet.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] To some extent it can be calculated from the device properties.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Q factor, which is related to ESR and is sometimes a more convenient parameter than ESR to use in calculations of high-frequency non-ideal performance of real inductors, is quoted in inductor data sheets.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Capacitors, inductors, and resistors are usually designed to minimise other parameters.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] In many cases this can be done to a sufficient extent that *parasitic* capacitance and inductance of a resistor, for example, are so small as not to affect circuit operation.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] However, under some circumstances parasitics become important and even dominant.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Pure capacitors and inductors do not dissipate energy; any component which dissipates energy must be treated in an equivalent circuit model incorporating one or more resistors.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Actual passive two-terminal components can be represented by some network of lumped and distributed ideal inductors, capacitors, and resistors, in the sense that the real component behaves as the network does.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Some of the components of the equivalent circuit can vary with conditions, e.g., frequency and temperature.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] If driven by a periodic sinewave (alternating current) the component will be characterised by its complex impedance *Z*(ω) = *R* + *j* *X*(ω); the impedance can involve several minor resistances, inductances and capacitances in addition to the main property.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] These small deviations from the ideal behavior of the device can become significant under certain conditions, typically high frequency, where the reactance of small capacitances and inductances can become a significant element of circuit operation.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Models of lesser or greater complexity can be used, depending upon the accuracy required.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] For many purposes, a simple model with an inductance or capacitance in series with an ESR is good enough.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] These models, however simple or complex, can be inserted into a circuit to calculate performance.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Computer tools are available for complex circuits; e.g., the SPICE program and its variants.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] An inductor consists of a conducting insulated wire coil usually wound around a ferromagnetic core.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Inductors have resistance inherent in the metal conductor, quoted as DCR in datasheets.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] This metallic resistance is small for small inductance values (typically below 1 Ω).
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] The DC wire resistance is an important parameter in transformer and general inductor design because it contributes to the impedance of the component, and current flowing through that resistance is dissipated as waste heat, and energy is lost from the circuit.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] It can be modeled as a resistor in series with the inductor, often leading to the DC resistance being referred to as the ESR.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Though this is not precisely correct usage, the unimportant elements of ESR are often neglected in circuit discussion, since it is rare that all elements of ESR are significant to a particular application.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] An inductor using a core to increase inductance will have losses such as hysteresis and eddy current in the core.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] At high frequencies there are also losses in the windings due to proximity and skin effects.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] These are in addition to wire resistance, and lead to a higher ESR.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] In a non-electrolytic capacitor and electrolytic capacitors with solid electrolyte, the metallic resistance of the leads and electrodes and losses in the dielectric cause the ESR.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Typically quoted values of ESR for ceramic capacitors are between 0.01 and 0.1 Ω.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] ESR of non-electrolytic capacitors tends to be fairly stable over time; for most purposes real non-electrolytic capacitors can be treated as ideal components.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Aluminium and tantalum electrolytic capacitors with non solid electrolyte have much higher ESR values, up to several ohms; electrolytics of higher capacitance have lower ESR.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] ESR decreases with frequency up to the capacitor's self-resonant frequency.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] A very serious problem, particularly with aluminium electrolytics, is that ESR increases over time from evaporation and more importantly from oxygen being depleted in the electrolyte with use.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] ESR can increase enough to cause circuit malfunction and even component damage, although measured capacitance may remain within tolerance.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] While this happens with normal aging, high temperatures and large ripple current exacerbate the problem.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] In a circuit with significant ripple current, an increase in ESR will increase heat accumulation, thus accelerating aging.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Electrolytic capacitors rated for high-temperature operation and of higher quality than basic consumer-grade parts are less susceptible to become prematurely unusable due to ESR increase.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] A cheap electrolytic capacitor may be rated for a life of less than 1000 hours (6 weeks) at 85 °C.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Higher-grade parts are typically rated at a few thousand hours at maximum rated temperature, as can be seen from manufacturers' datasheets.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] If ESR is critical, specification of a part with higher temperature rating, "low ESR" or larger capacitance than is otherwise required may be advantageous.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] There is no standard for "low ESR" capacitor rating.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Polymer capacitors usually have lower ESR than wet-electrolytic of same value, and stable under varying temperature.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] Therefore, polymer capacitors can handle higher ripple current.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] From about 2007 it became common for better-quality computer motherboards to use only polymer capacitors where wet electrolytics had been used previously.
[src:supercapacitors/equivalent-series-resistance] The ESR of capacitors larger than about 1 μF is easily measured in-circuit with an ESR meter.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Faradaic pseudocapacitance only occurs together with static double-layer capacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Pseudocapacitance and double-layer capacitance both contribute inseparably to the total capacitance value.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The amount of pseudocapacitance depends on the surface area, material and structure of the electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Pseudocapacitance may contribute more capacitance than double-layer capacitance for the same surface area by 100x.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The amount of electric charge stored in a pseudocapacitance is linearly proportional to the applied voltage.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Redox reactions in batteries with faradaic charge-transfer between an electrolyte and the surface of an electrode were characterized decades ago.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] These chemical processes are associated with chemical reactions of the electrode materials usually with attendant phase changes.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Although these chemical processes are relatively reversible, battery charge/discharge cycles often irreversibly produce unreversed chemical reaction products of the reagents.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Accordingly, the cycle-life of rechargeable batteries is usually limited.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Further, the reaction products lower power density.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Additionally, the chemical processes are relatively slow, extending charge/discharge times.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] A fundamental difference between redox reactions in batteries and in electrochemical capacitors (supercapacitors) is that in the latter, the reactions are a very fast sequence of reversible processes with electron transfer without any phase changes of the electrode molecules.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] They do not involve making or breaking chemical bonds.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The de-solvated atoms or ions contributing the pseudocapacitance simply cling to the atomic structure of the electrode and charges are distributed on surfaces by physical adsorption processes.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Compared with batteries, supercapacitor faradaic processes are much faster and more stable over time, because they leave only traces of reaction products.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Despite the reduced amount of these products, they cause capacitance degradation.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] This behavior is the essence of pseudocapacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Pseudocapacitive processes lead to a charge-dependent, linear capacitive behavior, as well as the accomplishment of non-faradaic double-layer capacitance in contrast to batteries, which have a nearly charge-independent behavior.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The pseudocapacitance may exceed the value of double-layer capacitance for the same surface area by 100x.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Applying a voltage at the capacitor terminals moves the polarized ions or charged atoms in the electrolyte to the opposite polarized electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Between the surfaces of the electrodes and the adjacent electrolyte an electric double-layer forms.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] One layer of ions on the electrode surface and the second layer of adjacent polarized and solvated ions in the electrolyte move to the opposite polarized electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The two ion layers are separated by a single layer of electrolyte molecules.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Between the two layers, a static electric field forms that results in double-layer capacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Accompanied by the electric double-layer, some de-solvated electrolyte ions pervade the separating solvent layer and are adsorbed by the electrode's surface atoms.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] They are specifically adsorbed and deliver their charge to the electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] In other words, the ions in the electrolyte within the Helmholtz double-layer also act as electron donors and transfer electrons to the electrode atoms, resulting in a faradaic current.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] This faradaic charge transfer, originated by a fast sequence of reversible redox reactions, electrosorptions or intercalation processes between electrolyte and the electrode surface is called pseudocapacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Depending on the electrode's structure or surface material, pseudocapacitance can originate when specifically adsorbed ions pervade the double-layer, proceeding in several one-electron stages.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The electrons involved in the faradaic processes are transferred to or from the electrode's valence-electron states (orbitals) and flow through the external circuit to the opposite electrode where a second double-layer with an equal number of opposite-charged ions forms.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The electrons remain in the strongly ionized and electrode surface's "electron hungry" transition-metal ions and are not transferred to the adsorbed ions.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] This kind of pseudocapacitance has a linear function within narrow limits and is determined by the potential-dependent degree of surface coverage of the adsorbed anions.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The storage capacity of the pseudocapacitance is limited by the finite quantity of reagent or of available surface.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] All three types of electrochemical processes have appeared in supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] When discharging pseudocapacitance, the charge transfer is reversed and the ions or atoms leave the double-layer and spread throughout the electrolyte.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Electrodes' ability to produce pseudocapacitance strongly depends on the electrode materials' chemical affinity to the ions adsorbed on the electrode surface as well as on the electrode pore structure and dimension.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Materials exhibiting redox behavior for use as pseudocapacitor electrodes are transition-metal oxides inserted by doping in the conductive electrode material such as active carbon, as well as conducting polymers such as polyaniline or derivatives of polythiophene covering the electrode material.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] These materials provide high pseudocapacitance and were thoroughly studied by Conway.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Many oxides of transition metals like ruthenium (RuO 2), iridium (IrO 2), iron (Fe 3O 4), manganese (MnO 2) or sulfides such as titanium sulfide (TiS 2) or their combinations generate faradaic electron–transferring reactions with low conducting resistance.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Ruthenium dioxide (RuO 2) in combination with sulfuric acid (H 2SO 4) electrolyte provides one of the best examples of pseudocapacitance, with a charge/discharge over a window of about 1.2 V per electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Furthermore, the reversibility on these transition metal electrodes is excellent, with a cycle life of more than several hundred-thousand cycles.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Pseudocapacitance originates from a coupled, reversible redox reaction with several oxidation steps with overlapping potential.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The electrons mostly come from the electrode's valence orbitals.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The electron transfer reaction is very fast and can be accompanied with high currents.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] During charge and discharge, H+ (protons) are incorporated into or removed from the RuO 2 crystal lattice, which generates storage of electrical energy without chemical transformation.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The OH groups are deposited as a molecular layer on the electrode surface and remain in the region of the Helmholtz layer.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Since the measurable voltage from the redox reaction is proportional to the charged state, the reaction behaves like a capacitor rather than a battery, whose voltage is largely independent of the state of charge.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Another type of material with a high amount of pseudocapacitance is electron-conducting polymers.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Conductive polymer such as polyaniline, polythiophene, polypyrrole and polyacetylene have a lower reversibility of the redox processes involving faradaic charge transfer than transition metal oxides, and suffer from a limited stability during cycling.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Such electrodes employ electrochemical doping or dedoping of the polymers with anions and cations.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Highest capacitance and power density are achieved with a n/p-type polymer configuration, with one negatively charged (n-doped) and one positively charged (p-doped) electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Pseudocapacitance may originate from the electrode structure, especially from the material pore size.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The use of carbide-derived carbons (CDCs) or carbon nanotubes (CNTs) as electrodes provides a network of small pores formed by nanotube entanglement.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] These nanoporous materials have diameters in the range of <2 nm that can be referred to as intercalated pores.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Solvated ions in the electrolyte are unable to enter these small pores, but de-solvated ions that have reduced their ion dimensions are able to enter, resulting in larger ionic packing density and increased charge storage.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The tailored sizes of pores in nano-structured carbon electrodes can maximize ion confinement, increasing specific capacitance by faradaic H 2 adsorption treatment.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Occupation of these pores by de-solvated ions from the electrolyte solution occurs according to (faradaic) intercalation.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Pseudocapacitance properties can be expressed in a cyclic voltammogram.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] For an ideal double-layer capacitor, the current flow is reversed immediately upon reversing the potential yielding a rectangular-shaped voltammogram, with a current independent of the electrode potential.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] For double-layer capacitors with resistive losses, the shape changes to a parallelogram.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] In faradaic electrodes the electrical charge stored in the capacitor is strongly dependent on the potential, therefore, the voltammetry characteristics deviate from the parallelogram due to a delay while reversing the potential, ultimately coming from kinetic charging processes.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Brezesinki et al. showed that mesoporous films of *α*-MoO3 have improved charge storage due to lithium ions inserting into the gaps of *α*-MoO3.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] They claim this intercalation pseudocapacitance takes place on the same timescale as redox pseudocapacitance and gives better charge-storage capacity without changing kinetics in mesoporous MoO3.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] This approach is promising for batteries with rapid charging ability, comparable to that of lithium batteries, and is promising for efficient energy materials.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Other groups have used vanadium oxide thin films on carbon nanotubes for pseudocapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Kim et al. electrochemically deposited amorphous V2O5·xH2O onto a carbon nanotube film.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] The three-dimensional structure of the carbon nanotubes substrate facilitates high specific lithium-ion capacitance and shows three times higher capacitance than vanadium oxide deposited on a typical Pt substrate.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] These studies demonstrate the capability of deposited oxides to effectively store charge in pseudocapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Conducting polymers, such as polypyrrole (PPy) and poly(3,4-ethylenedioxythiophene) (PEDOT), have tunable electronic conductivity and can achieve high doping levels with the proper counterion.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] A high-performing conducting polymer pseudocapacitor has high cycling stability after undergoing charge/discharge cycles.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Successful approaches include embedding the redox polymer in a host phase (e.g. titanium carbide) for stability and depositing a carbonaceous shell onto the conducting polymer electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] These techniques improve cyclability and stability of the pseudocapacitor device.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Pseudocapacitance is used in processes that require High Power Faradaic Storage; for example: electrochemical capacitors, high-power batteries, capacitive deionization, and neuromorphic computing among others.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Materials that use pseudocapacitance are considered a great opportunity for achieving high rate, high energy density and high efficiency energy storage systems based on ion absorption and intercalation.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Using its working properties of electrosorption and surface redox process at high-area electrode materials; for example RuO2 improves the energy storage properties of one of a traditional capacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] In the recent study, “Pseudocapacitance phenomena and applications in biosensing devices” by Raphael M.B.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Bueno published in 2019, it was concluded that compounds with electrochemical capacitance or pseudocapacitance can be successfully used into the designed of interfaces for the biological detection of biomarkers.
[src:supercapacitors/pseudocapacitor] Due to their charge transfer reactions, pseudocapacitive materials can also be used in water deionization; the high ion storage capacities and fast storage time necessary for water purification is kept during the process using this type of materials.
[src:supercapacitors/ragone-plot] A **Ragone plot** (/rəˈɡoʊniː/ *rə-GOH-nee*) is a plot used for comparing the energy density of various energy-storing devices.
[src:supercapacitors/ragone-plot] On such a chart the values of specific energy (in W·h/kg) are plotted versus specific power (in W/kg).
[src:supercapacitors/ragone-plot] Both axes are logarithmic, which allows comparing performance of very different devices.
[src:supercapacitors/ragone-plot] Ragone plots can reveal information about gravimetric energy density, but do not convey details about volumetric energy density.
[src:supercapacitors/ragone-plot] The Ragone plot was first used to compare performance of batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/ragone-plot] However, it is suitable for comparing any energy-storage devices, as well as energy devices such as engines, gas turbines, and fuel cells.
[src:supercapacitors/ragone-plot] Conceptually, the vertical axis describes how much energy is available per unit mass, while the horizontal axis shows how quickly that energy can be delivered, otherwise known as power per unit mass.
[src:supercapacitors/ragone-plot] A point in a Ragone plot represents a particular energy device or technology.
[src:supercapacitors/ragone-plot] The amount of time (in hours) that a device can operate at its rated power is given by the ratio of its specific energy (Y-axis) to its specific power (X-axis).
[src:supercapacitors/ragone-plot] This relationship holds regardless of the device's overall size, as a larger device would have proportional increases in both energy and power.
[src:supercapacitors/ragone-plot] Consequently, the iso curves (constant operating time) in a Ragone plot are straight lines.
[src:supercapacitors/ragone-plot] where *V* is voltage (V), *I* electric current (A), *t* time (s) and *m* mass (kg).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] A **supercapacitor** (**SC**), also called an **ultracapacitor**, is a high-capacity capacitor, with a capacitance value much higher than solid-state capacitors but with lower voltage limits.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] It bridges the gap between electrolytic capacitors and rechargeable batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] It typically stores 10 to 100 times more energy per unit mass or energy per unit volume than electrolytic capacitors, can accept and deliver charge much faster than batteries, and tolerates many more charge and discharge cycles than rechargeable batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Unlike ordinary capacitors, supercapacitors do not use a conventional solid dielectric, but rather, they use electrostatic double-layer capacitance and electrochemical pseudocapacitance, both of which contribute to the total energy storage of the capacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Supercapacitors are used in applications requiring many rapid charge/discharge cycles, rather than long-term compact energy storage: in automobiles, buses, trains, cranes, and elevators they are used for regenerative braking, short-term energy storage, or burst-mode power delivery.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Smaller units are used as power backup for static random-access memory (SRAM).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In solid-state capacitors, the mobile charges are electrons, and the gap between electrodes is a layer of a dielectric.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In electrochemical double-layer capacitors, the mobile charges are solvated ions (cations and anions), and the effective thickness is determined on each of the two electrodes by their electrochemical double layer structure.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In batteries the charge is stored in the bulk volume of solid phases, which have both electronic and ionic conductivities.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In electrochemical supercapacitors, the charge storage mechanisms either combine the double-layer and battery mechanisms, or are based on mechanisms, which are intermediate between true double layer and true battery.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In the early 1950s, General Electric engineers began experimenting with porous carbon electrodes in the design of capacitors, from the design of fuel cells and rechargeable batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Activated charcoal is an electrical conductor that is an extremely porous "spongy" form of carbon with a high specific surface area.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Becker developed a "Low voltage electrolytic capacitor with porous carbon electrodes".
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] He believed that the energy was stored as a charge in the carbon pores as in the pores of the etched foils of electrolytic capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] General Electric did not immediately pursue this work.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In 1966 researchers at Standard Oil of Ohio (SOHIO) developed another version of the component as "electrical energy storage apparatus", while working on experimental fuel cell designs.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The nature of electrochemical energy storage was not described in this patent.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Even in 1970, the electrochemical capacitor patented by Donald L.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Boos was registered as an electrolytic capacitor with activated carbon electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Early electrochemical capacitors used two aluminum foils covered with activated carbon (the electrodes) that were soaked in an electrolyte and separated by a thin porous insulator.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] This design gave a capacitor with a capacitance on the order of one farad, significantly higher than electrolytic capacitors of the same dimensions.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] This basic mechanical design remains the basis of most electrochemical capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] SOHIO did not commercialize their invention, licensing the technology to NEC, who finally marketed the results as "supercapacitors" in 1978, to provide backup power for computer memory.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Between 1975 and 1980 Brian Evans Conway conducted extensive fundamental and development work on ruthenium oxide electrochemical capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In 1991 he described the difference between "supercapacitor" and "battery" behaviour in electrochemical energy storage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In 1999 he defined the term "supercapacitor" to make reference to the increase in observed capacitance by surface redox reactions with faradaic charge transfer between electrodes and ions.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] His "supercapacitor" stored electrical charge partially in the Helmholtz double-layer and partially as result of faradaic reactions with "pseudocapacitance" charge transfer of electrons and protons between electrode and electrolyte.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The working mechanisms of pseudocapacitors are redox reactions, intercalation and electrosorption (adsorption onto a surface).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] With his research, Conway greatly expanded the knowledge of electrochemical capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] That changed around 1978 as Panasonic marketed its Goldcaps brand.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] This product became a successful energy source for memory backup applications.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In 1987 ELNA "Dynacap"s entered the market.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] First generation EDLC's had relatively high internal resistance that limited the discharge current.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] They were used for low current applications such as powering SRAM chips or for data backup.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] At the end of the 1980s, improved electrode materials increased capacitance values.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] At the same time, the development of electrolytes with better conductivity lowered the equivalent series resistance (ESR) increasing charge/discharge currents.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The first supercapacitor with low internal resistance was developed in 1982 for military applications through the Pinnacle Research Institute (PRI), and were marketed under the brand name "PRI Ultracapacitor".
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In 1992, Maxwell Laboratories (later Maxwell Technologies) took over this development.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Maxwell adopted the term Ultracapacitor from PRI and called them "Boost Caps" to underline their use for power applications.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Since capacitors' energy content increases with the square of the voltage, researchers were looking for a way to increase the electrolyte's breakdown voltage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In 1994 using the anode of a 200 V high-voltage tantalum electrolytic capacitor, David A.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Evans developed an "Electrolytic-Hybrid Electrochemical Capacitor".
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] These capacitors combine features of electrolytic and electrochemical capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] They combine the high dielectric strength of an anode from an electrolytic capacitor with the high capacitance of a pseudocapacitive metal oxide (ruthenium (IV) oxide) cathode from an electrochemical capacitor, yielding a hybrid electrochemical capacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Evans' capacitors, coined Capattery, had an energy content about a factor of 5 higher than a comparable tantalum electrolytic capacitor of the same size.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Their high costs limited them to specific military applications.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Recent developments include lithium-ion capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] These hybrid capacitors were pioneered by Fujitsu's FDK in 2007.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] They combine an electrostatic carbon electrode with a pre-doped lithium-ion electrochemical electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] This combination increases the capacitance value.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Additionally, the pre-doping process lowers the anode potential and results in a high cell output voltage, further increasing specific energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Research departments active in many companies and universities are working to improve characteristics such as specific energy, specific power, and cycle stability and to reduce production costs.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Electrochemical capacitors (supercapacitors) consist of two electrodes separated by an ion-permeable membrane (separator), and an electrolyte ionically connecting both electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] When the electrodes are polarized by an applied voltage, ions in the electrolyte form electric double layers of opposite polarity to the electrode's polarity.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] For example, positively polarized electrodes will have a layer of negative ions at the electrode/electrolyte interface along with a charge-balancing layer of positive ions adsorbing onto the negative layer.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The opposite is true for the negatively polarized electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Additionally, depending on electrode material and surface shape, some ions may permeate the double layer becoming specifically adsorbed ions and contribute with pseudocapacitance to the total capacitance of the supercapacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The two electrodes form a series circuit of two individual capacitors ⁠ $C_{1}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $C_{2}$ ⁠.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Supercapacitors may have either symmetric or asymmetric electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Symmetry implies that both electrodes have the same capacitance value, yielding a total capacitance of half the value of each single electrode (if ⁠ $C_{1}=C_{2}$ ⁠, then ⁠ $\textstyle C_{\mathrm {total} }={1 \over 2}C_{1}$ ⁠).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] For asymmetric capacitors, the total capacitance can be taken as that of the electrode with the smaller capacitance (if ⁠ $C_{1}\gg C_{2}$ ⁠, then ⁠ $C_{\mathrm {total} }\approx C_{2}$ ⁠).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Electrochemical capacitors use the double-layer effect to store electric energy; however, this double-layer has no conventional solid dielectric to separate the charges.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Both capacitances are only separable by measurement techniques.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The amount of charge stored per unit voltage in an electrochemical capacitor is primarily a function of the electrode size, although the amount of capacitance of each storage principle can vary extremely.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Every electrochemical capacitor has two electrodes, mechanically separated by a separator, which are ionically connected to each other via the electrolyte.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The electrolyte is a mixture of positive and negative ions dissolved in a solvent such as water.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] At each of the two electrode surfaces originates an area in which the liquid electrolyte contacts the conductive metallic surface of the electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] This interface forms a common boundary among two different phases of matter, such as an insoluble solid electrode surface and an adjacent liquid electrolyte.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In this interface occurs a very special phenomenon of the double layer effect.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Applying a voltage to an electrochemical capacitor causes both electrodes in the capacitor to generate electrical double-layers.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] These double-layers consist of two layers of charges: one electronic layer is in the surface lattice structure of the electrode, and the other, with opposite polarity, emerges from dissolved and solvated ions in the electrolyte.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The two layers are separated by a monolayer of solvent molecules, e.g., for water as solvent by water molecules, called inner Helmholtz plane (IHP).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Solvent molecules adhere by physical adsorption on the surface of the electrode and separate the oppositely polarized ions from each other, and can be idealised as a molecular dielectric.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In the process, there is no transfer of charge between electrode and electrolyte, so the forces that cause the adhesion are not chemical bonds, but physical forces, e.g., electrostatic forces.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The adsorbed molecules are polarized, but, due to the lack of transfer of charge between electrolyte and electrode, suffered no chemical changes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The amount of charge in the electrode is matched by the magnitude of counter-charges in outer Helmholtz plane (OHP).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] This double-layer phenomena stores electrical charges as in a conventional capacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The double-layer charge forms a static electric field in the molecular layer of the solvent molecules in the IHP that corresponds to the strength of the applied voltage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The double-layer serves approximately as the dielectric layer in a conventional capacitor, albeit with the thickness of a single molecule.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Accordingly, capacitance ⁠ C ⁠ is greatest in capacitors made from materials with a high permittivity ⁠ $\varepsilon$ ⁠, large electrode plate surface areas ⁠ A ⁠ and small distance between plates ⁠ d ⁠.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] As a result, double-layer capacitors have much higher capacitance values than conventional capacitors, arising from the extremely large surface area of activated carbon electrodes and the extremely thin double-layer distance on the order of a few ångströms (0.3–0.8 nm), of order of the Debye length.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Assuming that the minimum distance between the electrode and the charge accumulating region cannot be less than the typical distance between negative and positive charges in atoms of ~0.05 nm a general capacitance upper limit of ~18 μF/cm2 has been predicted for non-faradaic capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The main drawback of carbon electrodes of double-layer supercapacitors is small values of quantum capacitance which act in series with capacitance of ionic space charge.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Therefore, further increase of density of capacitance in SCs can be connected with increasing of quantum capacitance of carbon electrode nanostructures.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The amount of charge stored per unit voltage in an electrochemical capacitor is primarily a function of the electrode size.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The electrostatic storage of energy in the double-layers is linear with respect to the stored charge, and correspond to the concentration of the adsorbed ions.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Also, while charge in conventional capacitors is transferred via electrons, capacitance in double-layer capacitors is related to the limited moving speed of ions in the electrolyte and the resistive porous structure of the electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Since no chemical changes take place within the electrode or electrolyte, charging and discharging electric double-layers in principle is unlimited.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Real supercapacitors lifetimes are only limited by electrolyte evaporation effects.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Applying a voltage at the electrochemical capacitor terminals moves electrolyte ions to the opposite polarized electrode and forms a double-layer in which a single layer of solvent molecules acts as separator.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Pseudocapacitance can originate when specifically adsorbed ions out of the electrolyte pervade the double-layer.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] This pseudocapacitance stores electrical energy by means of reversible faradaic redox reactions on the surface of suitable electrodes in an electrochemical capacitor with an electric double-layer.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Pseudocapacitance is accompanied with an electron charge-transfer between electrolyte and electrode coming from a de-solvated and adsorbed ion whereby only one electron per charge unit is participating.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] This faradaic charge transfer originates by a very fast sequence of reversible redox, intercalation or electrosorption processes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The adsorbed ion has no chemical reaction with the atoms of the electrode (no chemical bonds arise) since only a charge-transfer take place.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The electrons involved in the faradaic processes are transferred to or from valence electron states (orbitals) of the redox electrode reagent.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] They enter the negative electrode and flow through the external circuit to the positive electrode where a second double-layer with an equal number of anions has formed.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The electrons reaching the positive electrode are not transferred to the anions forming the double-layer, instead they remain in the strongly ionized and "electron hungry" transition-metal ions of the electrode's surface.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] As such, the storage capacity of faradaic pseudocapacitance is limited by the finite quantity of reagent in the available surface.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The amount of pseudocapacitance has a linear function within narrow limits determined by the potential-dependent degree of surface coverage of the adsorbed anions.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The ability of electrodes to accomplish pseudocapacitance effects by redox reactions, intercalation or electrosorption strongly depends on the chemical affinity of electrode materials to the ions adsorbed on the electrode surface as well as on the structure and dimension of the electrode pores.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The unit of pseudocapacitance is farad, same as that of capacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Although conventional battery-type electrode materials also use chemical reactions to store charge, they show very different electrical profiles, as the rate of discharge is limited by the speed of diffusion.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Grinding those materials down to nanoscale frees them of the diffusion limit and give them a more pseudocapacitative behavior, making them *extrinsic pseudocapacitors*.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Chodankar shows the representative voltage-capacity curves for bulk LiCoO2, nano LiCoO2, a redox pseudocapacitor (RuO2), and an intercalation pseudocapacitor (T−Nb2O5).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Supercapacitors can also be made with different materials and principles at the electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] If both of those materials use a fast, supercapacitor-type reaction (capacitance or pseudocapacitance), the result is called an asymmetric capacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The two electrodes have different electric potentials; when combined with proper balancing, the result is improved energy density with no loss of lifespan or current capacity.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] A number of newer supercapacitors are "hybrid": only one electrode uses a fast reaction (capacitance or pseudocapacitance), the other using a more "battery-like" (slower but higher-capacity) material.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Hybrid capacitors combine the rapid charge/discharge kinetics of electric double-layer capacitors (EDLCs) with the high energy density of pseudocapacitive or battery-type electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] These systems bridge the gap between conventional capacitors and batteries, making them critical for applications requiring both power and energy density.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] For example, an EDLC anode can be combined with an activated carbon–Ni(OH)2 cathode, the latter being a slow faradaic material.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The CV and GCD profiles of a hybrid capacitor have a shape between that of a battery and a supercapacitor, more similar to that of an SC.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Hybrid capacitors have much higher energy density, but have inferior cycle life and current capacity owing to the slower electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Conventional capacitors (also known as electrostatic capacitors), such as ceramic capacitors and film capacitors, consist of two electrodes separated by a dielectric material.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] When charged, the energy is stored in a static electric field that permeates the dielectric between the electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The total energy increases with the amount of stored charge, which in turn correlates linearly with the potential (voltage) between the plates.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The maximum potential difference between the plates (the maximal voltage) is limited by the dielectric's breakdown field strength.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The same static storage also applies for electrolytic capacitors in which most of the potential decreases over the anode's thin oxide layer.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The somewhat resistive liquid electrolyte (cathode) accounts for a small decrease of potential for "wet" electrolytic capacitors, while electrolytic capacitors with solid conductive polymer electrolyte this voltage drop is negligible.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In contrast, electrochemical capacitors (supercapacitors) consists of two electrodes separated by an ion-permeable membrane (separator) and electrically connected via an electrolyte.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Energy storage occurs within the double-layers of both electrodes as a mixture of a double-layer capacitance and pseudocapacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] When both electrodes have approximately the same resistance (internal resistance), the potential of the capacitor decreases symmetrically over both double-layers, whereby a voltage drop across the equivalent series resistance (ESR) of the electrolyte is achieved.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] For asymmetrical supercapacitors like hybrid capacitors the voltage drop between the electrodes could be asymmetrical.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The maximum potential across the capacitor (the maximal voltage) is limited by the electrolyte decomposition voltage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Both electrostatic and electrochemical energy storage in supercapacitors are linear with respect to the stored charge, just as in conventional capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The voltage between the capacitor terminals is linear with respect to the amount of stored energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Such linear voltage gradient differs from rechargeable electrochemical batteries, in which the voltage between the terminals remains independent of the amount of stored energy, providing a relatively constant voltage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Supercapacitors compete with electrolytic capacitors and rechargeable batteries, especially lithium-ion batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The following table compares the major parameters of the three main supercapacitor families with electrolytic capacitors and batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors feature nearly unlimited charge/discharge cycles, high dielectric strength (up to 550 V) and good frequency response as alternating current (AC) reactance in the lower frequency range.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Supercapacitors can store 10 to 100 times more energy than electrolytic capacitors, but they do not support AC applications.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] With regards to rechargeable batteries, supercapacitors feature higher peak currents, low cost per cycle, no danger of overcharging, good reversibility, non-corrosive electrolyte and low material toxicity.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Batteries offer lower purchase cost and stable voltage under discharge, but require complex electronic control and switching equipment, with consequent energy loss and spark hazard given a short.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Supercapacitors are made in different styles, such as flat with a single pair of electrodes, wound in a cylindrical case, or stacked in a rectangular case.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Because they cover a broad range of capacitance values, the size of the cases can vary.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Supercapacitors are constructed with two metal foils (current collectors), each coated with an electrode material such as activated carbon, which serve as the power connection between the electrode material and the external terminals of the capacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Specifically to the electrode material is a very large surface area.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In this example the activated carbon is electrochemically etched, so that the surface area of the material is about 100,000 times greater than the smooth surface.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The electrodes are kept apart by an ion-permeable membrane (separator) used as an insulator to protect the electrodes against short circuits.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] This construction is subsequently rolled or folded into a cylindrical or rectangular shape and can be stacked in an aluminum can or an adaptable rectangular housing.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The cell is then impregnated with a liquid or viscous electrolyte of organic or aqueous type.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The electrolyte, an ionic conductor, enters the pores of the electrodes and serves as the conductive connection between the electrodes across the separator.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Finally, the housing is hermetically sealed to ensure stable behavior over the specified lifetime.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Electrical energy is stored in supercapacitors via two storage principles, static double-layer capacitance and electrochemical pseudocapacitance; and the distribution of the two types of capacitance depends on the material and structure of the electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Because double-layer capacitance and pseudocapacitance both contribute inseparably to the total capacitance value of an electrochemical capacitor, a correct description of these capacitors only can be given under the generic term.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] The concepts of supercapattery and supercabattery have been recently proposed to better represent those hybrid devices that behave more like the supercapacitor and the rechargeable battery, respectively.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Double-layer capacitance and pseudocapacitance both contribute inseparably to the total capacitance value of a supercapacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] However, the ratio of the two can vary greatly, depending on the design of the electrodes and the composition of the electrolyte.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Pseudocapacitance can increase the capacitance value by as much as a factor of ten over that of the double-layer by itself.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Electric double-layer capacitors (EDLC) are electrochemical capacitors in which energy storage predominantly is achieved by double-layer capacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] In the past, all electrochemical capacitors were called "double-layer capacitors".
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p01] Contemporary usage sees double-layer capacitors, together with pseudocapacitors, as part of a larger family of electrochemical capacitors called supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The properties of supercapacitors come from the interaction of their internal materials.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Especially, the combination of electrode material and type of electrolyte determine the functionality and thermal and electrical characteristics of the capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Supercapacitor electrodes are generally thin coatings applied and electrically connected to a conductive, metallic current collector.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Electrodes must have good conductivity, high temperature stability, long-term chemical stability (inertness), high corrosion resistance and high surface areas per unit volume and mass.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Other requirements include environmental friendliness and low cost.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The amount of double-layer as well as pseudocapacitance stored per unit voltage in a supercapacitor is predominantly a function of the electrode surface area.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Therefore, supercapacitor electrodes are typically made of porous, spongy material with an extraordinarily high specific surface area, such as activated carbon.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Additionally, the ability of the electrode material to perform faradaic charge transfers enhances the total capacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Generally the smaller the electrode's pores, the greater the capacitance and specific energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] However, smaller pores increase equivalent series resistance (ESR) and decrease specific power.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Applications with high peak currents require larger pores and low internal losses, while applications requiring high specific energy need small pores.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The most commonly used electrode material for supercapacitors is carbon in various manifestations such as activated carbon (AC), carbon fibre-cloth (AFC), carbide-derived carbon (CDC), carbon aerogel, graphite (graphene), graphane and carbon nanotubes (CNTs).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Carbon-based electrodes exhibit predominantly static double-layer capacitance, even though a small amount of pseudocapacitance may also be present depending on the pore size distribution.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Pore sizes in carbons typically range from micropores (less than 2 nm) to mesopores (2-50 nm), but only micropores (<2 nm) contribute to pseudocapacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] As pore size approaches the solvation shell size, solvent molecules are excluded and only unsolvated ions fill the pores (even for large ions), increasing ionic packing density and storage capability by faradaic H 2 intercalation.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Activated carbon was the first material chosen for EDLC electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Even though its electrical conductivity is approximately 0.003% that of metals (1,250 to 2,000 S/m), it is sufficient for supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Activated carbon is an extremely porous form of carbon with a high specific surface area — a common approximation is that 1 gram (0.035 oz) (a pencil-eraser-sized amount) has a surface area of roughly 1,000 to 3,000 square metres (11,000 to 32,000 ft2) — about the size of 4 to 12 tennis courts.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The bulk form used in electrodes is low-density with many pores, giving high double-layer capacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Solid activated carbon, also termed *consolidated amorphous carbon* (CAC) is the most used electrode material for supercapacitors and may be cheaper than other carbon derivatives.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] It is produced from activated carbon powder pressed into the desired shape, forming a block with a wide distribution of pore sizes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] An electrode with a surface area of about 1000 m2/g results in a typical double-layer capacitance of about 10 μF/cm2 and a specific capacitance of 100 F/g.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] As of 2010 virtually all commercial supercapacitors use powdered activated carbon made from coconut shells.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Coconut shells produce activated carbon with more micropores than does charcoal made from wood.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Activated carbon fibres (ACF) are produced from activated carbon and have a typical diameter of 10 μm.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] They can have micropores with a very narrow pore-size distribution that can be readily controlled.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The surface area of ACF woven into a textile is about 2500 m2/g.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Advantages of ACF electrodes include low electrical resistance along the fibre axis and good contact to the collector.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] As for activated carbon, ACF electrodes exhibit predominantly double-layer capacitance with a small amount of pseudocapacitance due to their micropores.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Carbon aerogel is a highly porous, synthetic, ultralight material derived from an organic gel in which the liquid component of the gel has been replaced with a gas.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Aerogel electrodes are made via pyrolysis of resorcinol-formaldehyde aerogels and are more conductive than most activated carbons.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] They enable thin and mechanically stable electrodes with a thickness in the range of several hundred micrometres (μm) and with uniform pore size.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Aerogel electrodes also provide mechanical and vibration stability for supercapacitors used in high-vibration environments.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Researchers have created a carbon aerogel electrode with gravimetric densities of about 400–1200 m2/g and volumetric capacitance of 104 F/cm3, yielding a specific energy of 325 kJ/kg (90 Wh/kg) and specific power of 20 W/g.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Standard aerogel electrodes exhibit predominantly double-layer capacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Aerogel electrodes that incorporate composite material can add a high amount of pseudocapacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Carbide-derived carbons can exhibit high surface area and tunable pore diameters (from micropores to mesopores) to maximize ion confinement, increasing pseudocapacitance by faradaic H 2 adsorption treatment.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] CDC electrodes with tailored pore design offer as much as 75% greater specific energy than conventional activated carbons.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] As of 2015, a CDC supercapacitor offered a specific energy of 10.1 Wh/kg, 3,500 F capacitance and over one million charge-discharge cycles.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Graphene is a one-atom thick sheet of graphite, with atoms arranged in a regular hexagonal pattern, also called "nanocomposite paper".
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Graphene has a theoretical specific surface area of 2630 m2/g which can theoretically lead to a capacitance of 550 F/g.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] In addition, an advantage of graphene over activated carbon is its higher electrical conductivity.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] As of 2012, a new development used graphene sheets directly as electrodes without collectors for portable applications.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] In one embodiment, a graphene-based supercapacitor uses curved graphene sheets that do not stack face-to-face, forming mesopores that are accessible to and wettable by ionic electrolytes at voltages up to 4 V.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] A specific energy of 85.6 Wh/kg (308 kJ/kg) is obtained at room temperature equaling that of a conventional nickel–metal hydride battery, but with 100–1000 times greater specific power.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The two-dimensional structure of graphene improves charging and discharging.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Charge carriers in vertically oriented sheets can quickly migrate into or out of the deeper structures of the electrode, thus increasing currents.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Such capacitors may be suitable for 100/120 Hz filter applications, which are unreachable for supercapacitors using other carbon materials.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Chemical vapor deposition is a popular fabrication method for graphene utilized in supercapacitors, producing a high quality monolayer or few-layer graphene.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The process begins by introducing a Hydrocarbon (most commonly methane, CH4) into a reaction chamber.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] A metal catalyst such as copper (Cu) or nickel (Ni) are then placed in the reaction chamber to act as a substrate.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] These metals are frequently used due to their ability to decompose methane into free carbon atoms that will be used in the graphene formation.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The chamber is then heated to temperatures between 700 and 1000 degrees Celsius in order to decompose the methane molecules at the surface of the substrate.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The methane is decomposed into hydrogen gas (H2) that is vented from the chamber, and Carbon (C) atoms are released onto the substrate.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] As Carbon atoms are absorbed onto the substrate, they begin to diffuse along the surface and nucleate.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The Carbon atoms will naturally arrange themselves in the honeycomb lattice of graphene.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Depending on the temperature, pressure, and concentration of methane, the number of graphene layers produced will vary.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Once the graphene layer is formed, the chamber is cooled down and the now coated substrate is removed.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The graphene is then transferred from its metal substrate onto a new surface, depending on the application.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The method to perform this transfer is typically a PMMA-mediated approach (poly methyl-methacrylate).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Graphene is especially valuable in Supercapacitors due to its low-resistance pathways for electron flow, which is an essential part of the high power output of supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Mechanical exfoliation is another fabrication method for graphene sheets used in supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The process begins by selecting a high quality graphite, with high purity single-crystal graphite preferred.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Next, select a piece of tape that can peel off thin layers of the graphite without taking off large chunks of the material, scotch tape is frequently used in this method.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Repeatedly press the tape onto the graphite and gently peel it off.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] As the process is repeated, thinner and thinner graphene sheets will be transferred onto the tape.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Once a thin graphene layer has been pressed onto the tape, the tape is positioned on a clean substrate such as a silicon wafer or film.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The tape with the graphene is pressed gently onto the substrate to transfer the graphene layers to the surface of the substrate and then slowly peeled off.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] MnO2 and RuO2 are typical materials used as electrodes for pseudocapacitors, since they have the electrochemical signature of a capacitive electrode (linear dependence on current versus voltage curve) as well as exhibiting aic behavior.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Additionally, the charge storage originates from electron-transfer mechanisms rather than accumulation of ions in the electrochemical double layer.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Pseudocapacitors were created through faradaic redox reactions that occur within the active electrode materials.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] More research was focused on transition-metal oxides such as MnO2 since transition-metal oxides have a lower cost compared to noble metal oxides such as RuO2.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Moreover, the charge storage mechanisms of transition-metal oxides are based predominantly on pseudocapacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Two mechanisms of MnO2 charge storage behavior were introduced.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The first mechanism implies the intercalation of protons (H+) or alkali metal cations (C+) in the bulk of the material upon reduction followed by deintercalation upon oxidation.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The second mechanism is based on the surface adsorption of electrolyte cations on MnO2.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Not every material that exhibits faradaic behavior can be used as an electrode for pseudocapacitors, such as Ni(OH)2 since it is a battery type electrode (non-linear dependence on current versus voltage curve).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Brian Evans Conway's research described electrodes of transition metal oxides that exhibited high amounts of pseudocapacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Oxides of transition metals including ruthenium (RuO 2), iridium (IrO 2), iron (Fe 3O 4), manganese (MnO 2) or sulfides such as titanium sulfide (TiS 2) alone or in combination generate strong faradaic electron–transferring reactions combined with low resistance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Ruthenium dioxide in combination with H 2SO 4 electrolyte provides specific capacitance of 720 F/g and a high specific energy of 26.7 Wh/kg (96.12 kJ/kg).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Charge/discharge takes place over a window of about 1.2 V per electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] This pseudocapacitance of about 720 F/g is roughly 100 times higher than for double-layer capacitance using activated carbon electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] These transition metal electrodes offer excellent reversibility, with several hundred-thousand cycles.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] However, ruthenium is expensive and the 2.4 V voltage window for this capacitor limits their applications to military and space applications.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Das et al. reported highest capacitance value (1715 F/g) for ruthenium oxide based supercapacitor with electrodeposited ruthenium oxide onto porous single wall carbon nanotube film electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] A high specific capacitance of 1715 F/g has been reported which closely approaches the predicted theoretical maximum RuO 2 capacitance of 2000 F/g.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] In 2014, a RuO 2 supercapacitor anchored on a graphene foam electrode delivered specific capacitance of 502.78 F/g and areal capacitance of 1.11 F/cm2) leading to a specific energy of 39.28 Wh/kg and specific power of 128.01 kW/kg over 8,000 cycles with constant performance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The device was a three-dimensional (3D) sub-5 nm hydrous ruthenium-anchored graphene and carbon nanotube (CNT) hybrid foam (RGM) architecture.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The graphene foam was conformally covered with hybrid networks of RuO 2 nanoparticles and anchored CNTs.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Less expensive oxides of iron, vanadium, nickel and cobalt have been tested in aqueous electrolytes, but none has been investigated as much as manganese dioxide (MnO 2).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] However, none of these oxides are in commercial use.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Another approach uses electron-conducting polymers as pseudocapacitive material.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Although mechanically weak, conductive polymers have high conductivity, resulting in a low ESR and a relatively high capacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Such conducting polymers include polyaniline, polythiophene, polypyrrole and polyacetylene.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Such electrodes also employ electrochemical doping or dedoping of the polymers with anions and cations.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Electrodes made from, or coated with, conductive polymers have costs comparable to carbon electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Conducting polymer electrodes generally suffer from limited cycling stability.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] However, polyacene electrodes provide up to 10,000 cycles, much better than batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] All commercial hybrid supercapacitors are asymmetric.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] They combine an electrode with high amount of pseudocapacitance with an electrode with a high amount of double-layer capacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] In such systems the faradaic pseudocapacitance electrode with their higher capacitance provides high specific energy while the non-faradaic EDLC electrode enables high specific power.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] An advantage of the hybrid-type supercapacitors compared with symmetrical EDLC's is their higher specific capacitance value as well as their higher rated voltage and correspondingly their higher specific energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Closed-loop recycling recovers 92% of activated carbon from spent electrodes, reducing reliance on critical materials like cobalt.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Department of Energy's *Critical Material Innovation Program* funds research into graphene-carbon nanotube hybrids, aiming to reduce production costs by 40% by 2030.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Composite electrodes for hybrid-type supercapacitors are constructed from carbon-based material with incorporated or deposited pseudocapacitive active materials like metal oxides and conducting polymers.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] As of 2013 most research for supercapacitors explores composite electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] CNTs give a backbone for a homogeneous distribution of metal oxide or electrically conducting polymers (ECPs), producing good pseudocapacitance and good double-layer capacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] These electrodes achieve higher capacitances than either pure carbon or pure metal oxide or polymer-based electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] This is attributed to the accessibility of the nanotubes' tangled mat structure, which allows a uniform coating of pseudocapacitive materials and three-dimensional charge distribution.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The process to anchor pseudocapactive materials usually uses a hydrothermal process.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] However, a recent researcher, Li et al., from the University of Delaware found a facile and scalable approach to precipitate MnO2 on a SWNT film to make an organic-electrolyte based supercapacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Another way to enhance CNT electrodes is by doping with a pseudocapacitive dopant as in lithium-ion capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] In this case the relatively small lithium atoms intercalate between the layers of carbon.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The anode is made of lithium-doped carbon, which enables lower negative potential with a cathode made of activated carbon.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] This results in a larger voltage of 3.8-4 V that prevents electrolyte oxidation.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] As of 2007 they had achieved capacitance of 550 F/g. and reach a specific energy up to 14 Wh/kg (50.4 kJ/kg).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Rechargeable battery electrodes influenced the development of electrodes for new hybrid-type supercapacitor electrodes as for lithium-ion capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Together with a carbon EDLC electrode in an asymmetric construction offers this configuration higher specific energy than typical supercapacitors with higher specific power, longer cycle life and faster charging and recharging times than batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Recently some asymmetric hybrid supercapacitors were developed in which the positive electrode were based on a real pseudocapacitive metal oxide electrode (not a composite electrode), and the negative electrode on an EDLC activated carbon electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Asymmetric supercapacitors (ASC) have shown a great potential candidate for high-performance supercapacitor due to their wide operating potential which can remarkably enhance the capacitive behavior.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] An advantage of this type of supercapacitors is their higher voltage and correspondingly their higher specific energy (up to 10-20 Wh/kg (36-72 kJ/kg)).And they also have good cycling stability.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] For example, researchers use a kind of novel skutterudite Ni–CoP3 nanosheets and use it as positive electrodes with activated carbon (AC) as negative electrodes to fabricate asymmetric supercapacitor (ASC).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] It exhibits high energy density of 89.6 Wh/kg at 796 W/kg and stability of 93% after 10,000 cycles, which can be a great potential to be an excellent next-generation electrode candidate.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Also, carbon nanofibers/poly(3,4-ethylenedioxythiophene)/manganese oxide (f-CNFs/PEDOT/MnO2) were used as positive electrodes and AC as negative electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] It has high specific energy of 49.4 Wh/kg and good cycling stability (81.06% after cycling 8000 times).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Besides, many kinds of nanocomposite are being studied as electrodes, like NiCo2S4@NiO, MgCo2O4@MnO2 and so on.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] For example, Fe-SnO2@CeO2 nanocomposite used as electrode can provide a specific energy and specific power of 32.2 Wh/kg and 747 W/kg.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The device exhibited the capacitance retention of 85.05% over 5000 cycles of operation.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] As far as known no commercial offered supercapacitors with such kind of asymmetric electrodes are on the market.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Electrolytes consist of a solvent and dissolved chemicals that dissociate into positive cations and negative anions, making the electrolyte electrically conductive.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The more ions the electrolyte contains, the better its conductivity.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] In supercapacitors electrolytes are the electrically conductive connection between the two electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Additionally, in supercapacitors the electrolyte provides the molecules for the separating monolayer in the Helmholtz double-layer and delivers the ions for pseudocapacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The electrolyte determines the capacitor's characteristics: its operating voltage, temperature range, ESR and capacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] With the same activated carbon electrode an aqueous electrolyte achieves capacitance values of 160 F/g, while an organic electrolyte achieves only 100 F/g.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The electrolyte must be chemically inert and not chemically attack the other materials in the capacitor to ensure long time stable behavior of the capacitor's electrical parameters.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The electrolyte's viscosity must be low enough to wet the porous, sponge-like structure of the electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] An ideal electrolyte does not exist, forcing a compromise between performance and other requirements.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Water is a relatively good solvent for inorganic chemicals.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Aqueous electrolytes have a dissociation voltage of 1.15 V per electrode (2.3 V capacitor voltage) and a relatively low operating temperature range.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] They are used in supercapacitors with low specific energy and high specific power.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The lower electrical conductivity of organic solvents (10 to 60 mS/cm) leads to a lower specific power, but since the specific energy increases with the square of the voltage, a higher specific energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Ionic electrolytes consists of liquid salts that can be stable in a wider electrochemical window, enabling capacitor voltages above 3.5 V.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Ionic electrolytes typically have an ionic conductivity of a few mS/cm, lower than aqueous or organic electrolytes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Separators have to physically separate the two electrodes to prevent a short circuit by direct contact.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] It can be very thin (a few hundredths of a millimeter) and must be very porous to the conducting ions to minimize ESR.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Furthermore, separators must be chemically inert to protect the electrolyte's stability and conductivity.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Inexpensive components use open capacitor papers.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] More sophisticated designs use nonwoven porous polymeric films like polyacrylonitrile or Kapton, woven glass fibers or porous woven ceramic fibres.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] Current collectors connect the electrodes to the capacitor's terminals.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] The collector is either sprayed onto the electrode or is a metal foil.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] They must be able to distribute peak currents of up to 100 A.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p02] If the housing is made of a metal (typically aluminum), the collectors should be made from the same material to avoid forming a corrosive galvanic cell.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Capacitance values for commercial capacitors are specified as "rated capacitance CR".
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This is the value for which the capacitor has been designed.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The value for an actual component must be within the limits given by the specified tolerance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Typical values are in the range of farads (F), three to six orders of magnitude larger than those of electrolytic capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The capacitance value results from the energy W (expressed in Joule) of a loaded capacitor loaded via a DC voltage VDC.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This value is also called the "DC capacitance".
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Conventional capacitors are normally measured with a small AC voltage (0.5 V) and a frequency of 100 Hz or 1 kHz depending on the capacitor type.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The AC capacitance measurement offers fast results, important for industrial production lines.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The capacitance value of a supercapacitor depends strongly on the measurement frequency, which is related to the porous electrode structure and the limited electrolyte's ion mobility.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Even at a low frequency of 10 Hz, the measured capacitance value drops from 100 to 20 percent of the DC capacitance value.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This extraordinarily strong frequency dependence can be explained by the different distances the ions have to move in the electrode's pores.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The area at the beginning of the pores can be easily accessed by the ions; this short distance is accompanied by low electrical resistance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The greater the distance the ions have to cover, the higher the resistance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This phenomenon can be described with a series circuit of cascaded RC (resistor/capacitor) elements with serial RC time constants.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] These result in delayed current flow, reducing the total electrode surface area that can be covered with ions if polarity changes – capacitance decreases with increasing AC frequency.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Thus, the total capacitance is achieved only after longer measuring times.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Out of the reason of the very strong frequency dependence of the capacitance, this electrical parameter has to be measured with a special constant current charge and discharge measurement, defined in IEC standards 62391-1 and -2.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Measurement starts with charging the capacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The voltage has to be applied and after the constant current/constant voltage power supply has achieved the rated voltage, the capacitor must be charged for 30 minutes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Next, the capacitor has to be discharged with a constant discharge current Idischarge.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Then the time t1 and t2, for the voltage to drop from 80% (V1) to 40% (V2) of the rated voltage is measured.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The value of the discharge current is determined by the application.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The measurement methods employed by individual manufacturers are mainly comparable to the standardized methods.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The standardized measuring method is too time-consuming for manufacturers to use during production for each individual component.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] For industrial-produced capacitors, the capacitance value is instead measured with a faster, low-frequency AC voltage, and a correlation factor is used to compute the rated capacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This frequency dependence affects capacitor operation.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Rapid charge and discharge cycles mean that neither the rated capacitance value nor specific energy are available.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In this case the rated capacitance value is recalculated for each application condition.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] as the capacitor voltage decreases from Ucharge down to Umin.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] wherein also the capacitor voltage decreases from Ucharge down to Umin.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors are low voltage components.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Safe operation requires that the voltage remain within specified limits.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The rated voltage UR is the maximum DC voltage or peak pulse voltage that may be applied continuously and remain within the specified temperature range.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Capacitors should never be subjected to voltages continuously in excess of the rated voltage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The rated voltage includes a safety margin against the electrolyte's breakdown voltage at which the electrolyte decomposes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The breakdown voltage decomposes the separating solvent molecules in the Helmholtz double-layer, e.g. water splits into hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The solvent molecules then cannot separate the electrical charges from each other.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Higher voltages than rated voltage cause hydrogen gas formation or a short circuit.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Standard supercapacitors with aqueous electrolyte normally are specified with a rated voltage of 2.1 to 2.3 V and capacitors with organic solvents with 2.5 to 2.7 V.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Lithium-ion capacitors with doped electrodes may reach a rated voltage of 3.8 to 4 V, but have a low voltage limit of about 2.2 V.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors with ionic electrolytes can exceed an operating voltage of 3.5 V.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Operating supercapacitors below the rated voltage improves the long-time behavior of the electrical parameters.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Capacitance values and internal resistance during cycling are more stable and lifetime and charge/discharge cycles may be extended.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Higher application voltages require connecting cells in series.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Since each component has a slight difference in capacitance value and ESR, it is necessary to actively or passively balance them to stabilize the applied voltage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Passive balancing employs resistors in parallel with the supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Active balancing may include electronic voltage management above a threshold that varies the current.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Charging/discharging a supercapacitor is connected to the movement of charge carriers (ions) in the electrolyte across the separator to the electrodes and into their porous structure.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Losses occur during this movement that can be measured as the internal DC resistance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] With the electrical model of cascaded, series-connected RC (resistor/capacitor) elements in the electrode pores, the internal resistance increases with the increasing penetration depth of the charge carriers into the pores.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The internal DC resistance is time dependent and increases during charge/discharge.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In applications often only the switch-on and switch-off range is interesting.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The internal resistance Ri can be calculated from the voltage drop ΔV2 at the time of discharge, starting with a constant discharge current Idischarge.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] It is obtained from the intersection of the auxiliary line extended from the straight part and the time base at the time of discharge start (see picture right).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The discharge current Idischarge for the measurement of internal resistance can be taken from the classification according to IEC 62391-1.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This internal DC resistance Ri should not be confused with the internal AC resistance called equivalent series resistance (ESR) normally specified for capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] ESR is not relevant for calculating supercapacitor inrush currents or other peak currents.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Ri determines several supercapacitor properties.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] It limits the charge and discharge peak currents as well as charge/discharge times.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This time constant determines the charge/discharge time.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] A 100 F capacitor with an internal resistance of 30 mΩ for example, has a time constant of 0.03 • 100 = 3 s.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] After 3 seconds charging with a current limited only by internal resistance, the capacitor has 63.2% of full charge (or is discharged to 36.8% of full charge).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Standard capacitors with constant internal resistance fully charge during about 5 $\tau$ .
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Since internal resistance increases with charge/discharge, actual times cannot be calculated with this formula.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Thus, charge/discharge time depends on specific individual construction details.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Because supercapacitors operate without forming chemical bonds, current loads, including charge, discharge and peak currents are not limited by reaction constraints.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Current load and cycle stability can be much higher than for rechargeable batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Current loads are limited only by internal resistance, which may be substantially lower than for batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This heat must be released and distributed to the ambient environment to maintain operating temperatures below the specified maximum temperature.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Heat generally defines capacitor lifetime due to electrolyte diffusion.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The heat generation coming from current loads should be smaller than 5 to 10 K at maximum ambient temperature (which has only minor influence on expected lifetime).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] For that reason the specified charge and discharge currents for frequent cycling are determined by internal resistance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The specified cycle parameters under maximal conditions include charge and discharge current, pulse duration and frequency.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] They are specified for a defined temperature range and over the full voltage range for a defined lifetime.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] They can differ enormously depending on the combination of electrode porosity, pore size and electrolyte.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Generally a lower current load increases capacitor life and increases the number of cycles.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This can be achieved either by a lower voltage range or slower charging and discharging.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors (except those with polymer electrodes) can potentially support more than one million charge/discharge cycles without substantial capacity drops or internal resistance increases.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Beneath the higher current load is this the second great advantage of supercapacitors over batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The stability results from the dual electrostatic and electrochemical storage principles.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The specified charge and discharge currents can be significantly exceeded by lowering the frequency or by single pulses.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Heat generated by a single pulse may be spread over the time until the next pulse occurs to ensure a relatively small average heat increase.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Such a "peak power current" for power applications for supercapacitors of more than 1000 F can provide a maximum peak current of about 1000 A.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Such high currents generate high thermal stress and high electromagnetic forces that can damage the electrode-collector connection requiring robust design and construction of the capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Device parameters such as capacitance initial resistance and steady state resistance are not constant, but are variable and dependent on the device's operating voltage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Device capacitance will have a measurable increase as the operating voltage increases.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] For example: a 100F device can be seen to vary 26% from its maximum capacitance over its entire operational voltage range.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Similar dependence on operating voltage is seen in steady state resistance (Rss) and initial resistance (Ri).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Device properties can also be seen to be dependent on device temperature.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] As the temperature of the device changes either through operation of varying ambient temperature, the internal properties such as capacitance and resistance will vary as well.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Device capacitance is seen to increase as the operating temperature increases.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors occupy the gap between high power/low energy electrolytic capacitors and low power/high energy rechargeable batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This formula describes the amount of energy stored and is often used to describe new research successes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] However, only part of the stored energy is available to applications, because the voltage drop and the time constant over the internal resistance mean that some of the stored charge is inaccessible.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This formula also represents the energy asymmetric voltage components such as lithium ion capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The amount of energy that can be stored in a capacitor *per mass* of that capacitor is called its specific energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Specific energy is measured gravimetrically (per unit of mass) in watt-hours per kilogram (Wh/kg).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The amount of energy can be stored in a capacitor *per volume* of that capacitor is called its energy density (also called volumetric specific energy in some literature).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Energy density is measured volumetrically (per unit of volume) in watt-hours per litre (Wh/L).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Units of liters and dm3 can be used interchangeably.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] As of 2013 commercial energy density varies widely, but in general range from around 5 to 8 Wh/L.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In comparison, petrol fuel has an energy density of 32.4 MJ/L or 9000 Wh/L.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Commercial specific energies range from around 0.5 to 15 Wh/kg.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] For comparison, an aluminum electrolytic capacitor stores typically 0.01 to 0.3 Wh/kg, while a conventional lead–acid battery stores typically 30 to 40 Wh/kg and modern lithium-ion batteries 100 to 265 Wh/kg.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors can therefore store 10 to 100 times more energy than electrolytic capacitors, but only one tenth as much as batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] For reference, petrol fuel has a specific energy of 44.4 MJ/kg or 12300 Wh/kg.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Although the specific energy of supercapacitors is defavorably compared with batteries, capacitors have the important advantage of the specific power.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Specific power describes the speed at which energy can be delivered to the load (or, in charging the device, absorbed from the generator).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The maximum power Pmax specifies the power of a theoretical rectangular single maximum current peak of a given voltage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] with V = voltage applied and Ri, the internal DC resistance of the capacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Just like specific energy, specific power is measured either gravimetrically in kilowatts per kilogram (kW/kg, specific power) or volumetrically in kilowatts per litre (kW/L, power density).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitor specific power is typically 10 to 100 times greater than for batteries and can reach values up to 15 kW/kg.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Ragone charts relate energy to power and are a valuable tool for characterizing and visualizing energy storage components.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] With such a diagram, the position of specific power and specific energy of different storage technologies is easily to compare, see diagram.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Since supercapacitors do not rely on chemical changes in the electrodes (except for those with polymer electrodes), lifetimes depend mostly on the rate of evaporation of the liquid electrolyte.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This evaporation is generally a function of temperature, current load, current cycle frequency and voltage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Current load and cycle frequency generate internal heat, so that the evaporation-determining temperature is the sum of ambient and internal heat.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This temperature is measurable as core temperature in the center of a capacitor body.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The higher the core temperature, the faster the evaporation, and the shorter the lifetime.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Evaporation generally results in decreasing capacitance and increasing internal resistance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] According to IEC/EN 62391-2, capacitance reductions of over 30%, or internal resistance exceeding four times its data sheet specifications, are considered "wear-out failures", implying that the component has reached end-of-life.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The capacitors are operable, but with reduced capabilities.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Whether the aberration of the parameters have any influence on the proper functionality depends on the application of the capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Such large changes of electrical parameters specified in IEC/EN 62391-2 are usually unacceptable for high current load applications.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Components that support high current loads use much smaller limits, *e.g.*, 20% loss of capacitance or double the internal resistance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The narrower definition is important for such applications, since heat increases linearly with increasing internal resistance, and the maximum temperature should not be exceeded.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Temperatures higher than specified can destroy the capacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The real application lifetime of supercapacitors, also called "service life," "life expectancy", or "load life", can reach 10 to 15 years or more, at room temperature.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Such long periods cannot be tested by manufacturers.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Hence, they specify the expected capacitor lifetime at the maximum temperature and voltage conditions.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The results are specified in datasheets using the notation "tested time (hours)/max. temperature (°C)," such as "5000 h/65 °C".
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] With this value, and expressions derived from historical data, lifetimes can be estimated for lower temperature conditions.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Datasheet lifetime specification is tested by the manufactures using an accelerated aging test called an "endurance test", with maximum temperature and voltage over a specified time.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] For a "zero defect" product policy, no wear out or total failure may occur during this test.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The lifetime specification from datasheets can be used to estimate the expected lifetime for a given design.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The "10-degrees-rule" used for electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolyte is used in those estimations, and can be used for supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This rule employs the Arrhenius equation: a simple formula for the temperature dependence of reaction rates.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] For every 10 °C reduction in operating temperature, the estimated life doubles.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Calculated with this formula, capacitors specified with 5000 h at 65 °C, have an estimated lifetime of 20,000 h at 45 °C.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Lifetimes are also dependent on the operating voltage, because the development of gas in the liquid electrolyte depends on the voltage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The lower the voltage, the smaller the gas development, and the longer the lifetime.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] No general formula relates voltage to lifetime.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The voltage dependent curves shown from the picture are an empirical result from one manufacturer.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Life expectancy for power applications may be also limited by current load or number of cycles.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This limitation has to be specified by the relevant manufacturer and is strongly type dependent.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Storing electrical energy in the double-layer separates the charge carriers within the pores by distances in the range of molecules.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Irregularities can occur over this short distance, leading to a small exchange of charge carriers and gradual discharge.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This self-discharge is called leakage current.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Leakage depends on capacitance, voltage, temperature, and the chemical stability of the electrode/electrolyte combination.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] At room temperature, leakage is so low that it is specified as time to self-discharge in hours, days, or weeks.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] As an example, a 5.5 V/F Panasonic "Goldcapacitor" specifies a voltage drop at 20 °C from 5.5 V to 3 V in 600 hours (25 days or 3.6 weeks) for a double cell capacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] It has been noticed that after the EDLC experiences a charge or discharge, the voltage will drift over time, relaxing toward its previous voltage level.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The observed relaxation can occur over several hours and is likely due to long diffusion time constants of the porous electrodes within the EDLC.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Since the positive and negative electrodes (or simply positrode and negatrode, respectively) of symmetric supercapacitors consist of the same material, theoretically supercapacitors have no true polarity and catastrophic failure does not normally occur.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] However reverse-charging a supercapacitor lowers its capacity, so it is recommended practice to maintain the polarity resulting from the formation of the electrodes during production.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Asymmetric supercapacitors are inherently polar.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Pseudocapacitor and hybrid supercapacitors which have electrochemical charge properties may not be operated with reverse polarity, precluding their use in AC operation.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] A bar in the insulating sleeve identifies the negative terminal in a polarized component.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In some literature, the terms "anode" and "cathode" are used in place of negative electrode and positive electrode.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Using anode and cathode to describe the electrodes in supercapacitors (and also rechargeable batteries, including lithium-ion batteries) can lead to confusion, because the polarity changes depending on whether a component is considered as a generator or as a consumer of current.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In electrochemistry, cathode and anode are related to reduction and oxidation reactions, respectively.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] However, in supercapacitors based on electric double-layer capacitance, there is no oxidation nor reduction reactions on any of the two electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Therefore, the concepts of cathode and anode do not apply.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The range of electrodes and electrolytes available yields a variety of components suitable for diverse applications.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The development of low-ohmic electrolyte systems, in combination with electrodes with high pseudocapacitance, enable many more technical solutions.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The following table shows differences among capacitors of various manufacturers in capacitance range, cell voltage, internal resistance (ESR, DC or AC value) and volumetric and gravimetric specific energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In the table, ESR refers to the component with the largest capacitance value of the respective manufacturer.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Roughly, they divide supercapacitors into two groups.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The first group offers greater ESR values of about 20 milliohms and relatively small capacitance of 0.1 to 470 F.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] These are "double-layer capacitors" for memory back-up or similar applications.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The second group offers 100 to 10,000 F with a significantly lower ESR value under 1 milliohm.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] These components are suitable for power applications.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] A correlation of some supercapacitor series of different manufacturers to the various construction features is provided in Pandolfo and Hollenkamp.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In commercial double-layer capacitors, or, more specifically, EDLCs in which energy storage is predominantly achieved by double-layer capacitance, energy is stored by forming an electrical double layer of electrolyte ions on the surface of conductive electrodes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Since EDLCs are not limited by the electrochemical charge transfer kinetics of batteries, they can charge and discharge at a much higher rate, with lifetimes of more than 1 million cycles.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The EDLC energy density is determined by operating voltage and the specific capacitance (farad/gram or farad/cm3) of the electrode/electrolyte system.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The specific capacitance is related to the Specific Surface Area (SSA) accessible by the electrolyte, its interfacial double-layer capacitance, and the electrode material density.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Commercial EDLCs are based on two symmetric electrodes impregnated with electrolytes comprising tetraethylammonium tetrafluoroborate salts in organic solvents.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Current EDLCs containing organic electrolytes operate at 2.7 V and reach energy densities around 5-8 Wh/kg and 7 to 10 Wh/L.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Graphene-based platelets with mesoporous spacer material is a promising structure for increasing the SSA of the electrolyte.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors vary sufficiently that they are rarely interchangeable, especially those with higher specific energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Applications range from low to high peak currents, requiring standardized test protocols.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Test specifications and parameter requirements are specified in the generic specification IEC/EN 62391–1, *Fixed electric double layer capacitors for use in electronic equipment*.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors have advantages in applications where a large amount of power is needed for a relatively short time, where a very high number of charge/discharge cycles or a longer lifetime is required.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Typical applications range from milliamp currents or milliwatts of power for up to a few minutes to several amps current or several hundred kilowatts power for much shorter periods.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors do not support alternating current (AC) applications.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In applications with fluctuating loads, such as laptop computers, PDAs, GPS, portable media players, hand-held devices, and photovoltaic systems, supercapacitors can stabilize the power supply.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors deliver power for photographic flashes in digital cameras and for LED flashlights that can be charged in much shorter periods of time, *e.g.*, 90 seconds.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Some portable speakers are powered by supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] A cordless electric screwdriver with supercapacitors for energy storage has about half the run time of a comparable battery model, but can be fully charged in 90 seconds.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] It retains 85% of its charge after three months left idle.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Numerous non-linear loads, such as EV chargers, HEVs, air conditioning systems, and advanced power conversion systems cause current fluctuations and harmonics.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] These current differences create unwanted voltage fluctuations and therefore power oscillations on the grid.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Power oscillations not only reduce the efficiency of the grid, but can cause voltage drops in the common coupling bus, and considerable frequency fluctuations throughout the entire system.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] To overcome this problem, supercapacitors can be implemented as an interface between the load and the grid to act as a buffer between the grid and the high pulse power drawn from the charging station.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors provide backup or emergency shutdown power to low-power equipment such as RAM, SRAM, micro-controllers and PC Cards.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] They are the sole power source for low energy applications such as automated meter reading (AMR) equipment or for event notification in industrial electronics.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors buffer power to and from rechargeable batteries, mitigating the effects of short power interruptions and high current peaks.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Batteries kick in only during extended interruptions, *e.g.*, if the mains power or a fuel cell fails, which lengthens battery life.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Uninterruptible power supplies (UPS) may be powered by supercapacitors, which can replace much larger banks of electrolytic capacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This combination reduces the cost per cycle, saves on replacement and maintenance costs, enables the battery to be downsized and extends battery life.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors provide backup power for actuators in wind turbine pitch systems, so that blade pitch can be adjusted even if the main supply fails.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors can stabilize voltage fluctuations for powerlines by acting as dampers.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Wind and photovoltaic systems exhibit fluctuating supply evoked by gusting or clouds that supercapacitors can buffer within milliseconds.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Micro grids are usually powered by clean and renewable energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Most of this energy generation, however, is not constant throughout the day and does not usually match demand.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors can be used for micro grid storage to instantaneously inject power when the demand is high and the production dips momentarily, and to store energy in the reverse conditions.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] They are useful in this scenario, because micro grids are increasingly producing power in DC, and capacitors can be utilized in both DC and AC applications.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors work best in conjunction with chemical batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] They provide an immediate voltage buffer to compensate for quick changing power loads due to their high charge and discharge rate through an active control system.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Once the voltage is buffered, it is put through an inverter to supply AC power to the grid.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors cannot provide frequency correction in this form directly in the AC grid.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors are suitable temporary energy storage devices for energy harvesting systems.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In energy harvesting systems, the energy is collected from the ambient or renewable sources, *e.g.*, mechanical movement, light or electromagnetic fields, and converted to electrical energy in an energy storage device.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] For example, it was demonstrated that energy collected from RF (radio frequency) fields (using an RF antenna as an appropriate rectifier circuit) can be stored to a printed supercapacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The harvested energy was then used to power an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) for over 10 hours.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The UltraBattery is a hybrid rechargeable lead-acid battery and a supercapacitor.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Its cell construction contains a standard lead-acid battery positive electrode, standard sulphuric acid electrolyte and a specially prepared negative carbon-based electrode that store electrical energy with double-layer capacitance.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The presence of the supercapacitor electrode alters the chemistry of the battery and affords it significant protection from sulfation in high rate partial state of charge use, which is the typical failure mode of valve regulated lead-acid cells used this way.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The resulting cell performs with characteristics beyond either a lead-acid cell or a supercapacitor, with charge and discharge rates, cycle life, efficiency and performance all enhanced.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors are used in defibrillators where they can deliver 500 joules to shock the heart back into sinus rhythm.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors' low internal resistance supports applications that require short-term high currents.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Among the earliest uses were motor startup (cold engine starts, particularly with diesels) for large engines in tanks and submarines.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors buffer the battery, handling short current peaks, reducing cycling and extending battery life.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Further military applications that require high specific power are phased array radar antennae, laser power supplies, military radio communications, avionics displays and instrumentation, backup power for airbag deployment and GPS-guided missiles and projectiles.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] A primary challenge of all transport is reducing energy consumption and reducing CO 2 emissions.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Recovery of braking energy (recuperation or regenerative braking) helps with both.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This requires components that can quickly store and release energy over long times with a high cycle rate.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors fulfill these requirements and are therefore used in various applications in transportation.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In 2005, aerospace systems and controls company Diehl Luftfahrt Elektronik GmbH chose supercapacitors to power emergency actuators for doors and evacuation slides used in airliners, including the Airbus 380.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors can be used to supplement batteries in starter systems in diesel railroad locomotives with diesel–electric transmission.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The capacitors capture the braking energy of a full stop and deliver the peak current for starting the diesel engine and acceleration of the train and ensures the stabilization of line voltage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Depending on the driving mode up to 30% energy saving is possible by recovery of braking energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Low maintenance and environmentally friendly materials encouraged the choice of supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Mobile hybrid Diesel–electric rubber tyred gantry cranes move and stack containers within a terminal.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Lifting the boxes requires large amounts of energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Some of the energy could be recaptured while lowering the load, resulting in improved efficiency.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] A triple hybrid forklift truck uses fuel cells and batteries as primary energy storage and supercapacitors to buffer power peaks by storing braking energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] They provide the fork lift with peak power over 30 kW.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The triple-hybrid system offers over 50% energy savings compared with Diesel or fuel-cell systems.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitor-powered terminal tractors transport containers to warehouses.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] They provide an economical, quiet and pollution-free alternative to Diesel terminal tractors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors make it possible not only to reduce energy, but to replace overhead lines in historical city areas, so preserving the city's architectural heritage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This approach may allow many new light rail city lines to replace overhead wires that are too expensive to fully route.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In 2003 Mannheim adopted a prototype light-rail vehicle (LRV) using the MITRAC Energy Saver system from Bombardier Transportation to store mechanical braking energy with a roof-mounted supercapacitor unit.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] It contains several units each made of 192 capacitors with 2700 F / 2.7 V interconnected in three parallel lines.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This circuit results in a 518 V system with an energy content of 1.5 kWh.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] For acceleration when starting this "on-board-system" can provide the LRV with 600 kW and can drive the vehicle up to 1 km without overhead line supply, thus better integrating the LRV into the urban environment.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Compared to conventional LRVs or Metro vehicles that return energy into the grid, onboard energy storage saves up to 30% and reduces peak grid demand by up to 50%.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In 2009 supercapacitors enabled LRVs to operate in the historical city area of Heidelberg without overhead wires, thus preserving the city's architectural heritage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The SC equipment cost an additional €270,000 per vehicle, which was expected to be recovered over the first 15 years of operation.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The supercapacitors are charged at stop-over stations when the vehicle is at a scheduled stop.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In April 2011 German regional transport operator Rhein-Neckar, responsible for Heidelberg, ordered a further 11 units.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In 2009, Alstom and RATP equipped a Citadis tram with an experimental energy recovery system called "STEEM".
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The system is fitted with 48 roof-mounted supercapacitors to store braking energy, which provides tramways with a high level of energy autonomy by enabling them to run without overhead power lines on parts of its route, recharging while traveling on powered stop-over stations.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] During the tests, which took place between the Porte d'Italie and Porte de Choisy stops on line T3 of the tramway network in Paris, the tramset used an average of approximately 16% less energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In 2012 tram operator Geneva Public Transport began tests of an LRV equipped with a prototype roof-mounted supercapacitor unit to recover braking energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Siemens is delivering supercapacitor-enhanced light-rail transport systems that include mobile storage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Hong Kong's South Island metro line is to be equipped with two 2 MW energy storage units that are expected to reduce energy consumption by 10%.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In August 2012 the CSR Zhuzhou Electric Locomotive corporation of China presented a prototype two-car light metro train equipped with a roof-mounted supercapacitor unit.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The train can travel up 2 km without wires, recharging in 30 seconds at stations via a ground mounted pickup.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The supplier claimed the trains could be used in 100 small and medium-sized Chinese cities.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Seven trams (street cars) powered by supercapacitors were scheduled to go into operation in 2014 in Guangzhou, China.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The supercapacitors are recharged in 30 seconds by a device positioned between the rails.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] That powers the tram for up to 4 kilometres (2.5 mi).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] As of 2017, Zhuzhou's supercapacitor vehicles are also used on the new Nanjing streetcar system, and are undergoing trials in Wuhan.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In 2012, in Lyon (France), the SYTRAL (Lyon public transportation administration) started experiments of a "way side regeneration" system built by Adetel Group which has developed its own energy saver named "NeoGreen" for LRV, LRT and metros.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In 2014 China began using trams powered with supercapacitors that are recharged in 30 seconds by a device positioned between the rails, storing power to run the tram for up to 4 km — more than enough to reach the next stop, where the cycle can be repeated.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In 2015, Alstom announced SRS, an energy storage system that charges supercapacitors on board a tram by means of ground-level conductor rails located at tram stops.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This allows trams to operate without overhead lines for short distances.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The system has been touted as an alternative to the company's ground-level power supply (APS) system, or can be used in conjunction with it, as in the case of the VLT network in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, which opened in 2016.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] CAF also offers supercapacitors on their Urbos 3 trams in the form of their ACR system.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Maxwell Technologies, an American supercapacitor maker, claimed that more than 20,000 hybrid buses use the devices to increase acceleration, particularly in China.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The first hybrid electric bus with supercapacitors in Europe came in 2001 in Nuremberg, Germany.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] It was MAN's so-called "Ultracapbus", and was tested in real operation in 2001/2002.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The test vehicle was equipped with a diesel-electric drive in combination with supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The system was supplied with 8 Ultracap modules of 80 V, each containing 36 components.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The system worked with 640 V and could be charged/discharged at 400 A.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Its energy content was 0.4 kWh with a weight of 400 kg.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The supercapacitors recaptured braking energy and delivered starting energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Fuel consumption was reduced by 10 to 15% compared to conventional diesel vehicles.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Other advantages included reduction of CO 2 emissions, quiet and emissions-free engine starts, lower vibration and reduced maintenance costs.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] As of 2002 in Luzern, Switzerland an electric bus fleet called TOHYCO-Rider was tested.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The supercapacitors could be recharged via an inductive contactless high-speed power charger after every transportation cycle, within 3 to 4 minutes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In early 2005 Shanghai tested a new form of electric bus called capabus that runs without powerlines (catenary free operation) using large onboard supercapacitors that partially recharge whenever the bus is at a stop (under so-called electric umbrellas), and fully charge in the terminus.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In 2006, two commercial bus routes began to use the capabuses; one of them is route 11 in Shanghai.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] It was estimated that the supercapacitor bus was cheaper than a lithium-ion battery bus, and one of its buses had one-tenth the energy cost of a diesel bus with lifetime fuel savings of $200,000.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] A hybrid electric bus called tribrid was unveiled in 2008 by the University of Glamorgan, Wales, for use as student transport.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] It is powered by hydrogen fuel or solar cells, batteries and ultracapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] About 20% tank-to-wheel efficiency could be reached using the KERS system.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The Toyota TS030 Hybrid LMP1 car, a racing car developed under Le Mans Prototype rules, uses a hybrid drivetrain with supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In the 2012 24 Hours of Le Mans race a TS030 qualified with a fastest lap only 1.055 seconds slower (3:24.842 versus 3:23.787) than the fastest car, an Audi R18 e-tron quattro with flywheel energy storage.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The supercapacitor and flywheel components, whose rapid charge-discharge capabilities help in both braking and acceleration, made the Audi and Toyota hybrids the fastest cars in the race.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In the 2012 Le Mans race the two competing TS030s, one of which was in the lead for part of the race, both retired for reasons unrelated to the supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The TS030 won three of the 8 races in the 2012 FIA World Endurance Championship season.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In 2014 the Toyota TS040 Hybrid used a supercapacitor to add 480 horsepower from two electric motors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In 2024 the IndyCar racing series introduced a hybrid power system composed of 20 supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitor/battery combinations in electric vehicles (EV) and hybrid electric vehicles (HEV) are well investigated.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] A 20 to 60% fuel reduction has been claimed by recovering brake energy in EVs or HEVs.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The ability of supercapacitors to charge much faster than batteries, their stable electrical properties, broader temperature range and longer lifetime are suitable, but weight, volume and especially cost mitigate those advantages.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors' lower specific energy makes them unsuitable for use as a stand-alone energy source for long-distance driving.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The fuel economy improvement between a capacitor and a battery solution is about 20% and is available only for shorter trips.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] For long-distance driving the advantage decreases to 6%.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Vehicles combining capacitors and batteries run only in experimental vehicles.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] As of 2013 all automotive manufacturers of EV or HEVs have developed prototypes that uses supercapacitors instead of batteries to store braking energy in order to improve driveline efficiency.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The Mazda 6 was reportedly the first production car to use supercapacitors to recover braking energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Branded as i-eloop, the system stores energy in a supercapacitor during deceleration and uses it to power on-board electrical systems while the engine is stopped by the stop-start system.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The regenerative braking is claimed to reduce fuel consumption by about 10%.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The Toyota Yaris Hybrid-R concept car uses a supercapacitor to provide bursts of power.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] PSA Peugeot Citroën fit supercapacitors to some of its cars as part of its stop-start fuel-saving system, as this permits faster start-ups when the traffic lights turn green.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Russian Yo-cars Ё-mobile series was a concept and crossover hybrid vehicle working with a gasoline driven rotary vane type and an electric generator for driving the traction motors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] A supercapacitor with relatively low capacitance recovers brake energy to power the electric motor when accelerating from a stop.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] In Zell am See, Austria, an aerial lift connects the city with Schmittenhöhe mountain.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The gondolas sometimes run 24 hours per day, using electricity for lights, door opening and communication.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The only available time for recharging batteries at the stations is during the brief intervals of guest loading and unloading, which is too short to recharge batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitors offer a fast charge, higher number of cycles and longer life time than batteries.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Emirates Air Line (cable car), also known as the Thames cable car, is a 1-kilometre (0.62 mi) gondola line in London, UK, that crosses the Thames from the Greenwich Peninsula to the Royal Docks.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] The cabins are equipped with a modern infotainment system, which is powered by supercapacitors.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Within the two decades (2005-2025) there was a new family of supercapacitor applications emerged and known as Supercapacitor Assisted (SCA) techniques, based on the research happening at the University of Waikato in Hamilton, New Zealand.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] This SCA techniques family includes unique types of DC-DC converters, lightning protection systems, DC circuit breakers and DC powered appliances such as white goods etc.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] These techniques developed by the Waikato Power Electronics Research (WaiPER) group under the leadership of Prof Nihal Kularatna has culminated several patents, research publications and some commercial products such as Prodigy 8 series.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitor assisted low dropout regulator (SCALDO) is the first successful power converter technique under the SCA family.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitor assisted surge absorber (SCASA) is the first supercapacitor based surge protector technique which was commercialized by Thor Technologies, Perth, Australia.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] Supercapacitor assisted LED (SCALED) technique is a high efficiency DC lighting technique aimed at DC grid based future buildings.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] With future DC microgrid based DC systems developing, SCA Transient Energy Pump (SCATEP) based DC circuit breaker technique was also recently developed.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p03] SCA techniques are based on a unique new theoretical concept now published as SCA Loss Management (SCALoM) theory and this new family of power converters and protection systems are aimed at future DC microgrids, DC homes and DC appliances based on renewable energy.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p04] As of 2013 commercially available lithium-ion supercapacitors offered the highest gravimetric specific energy to date, reaching 15 Wh/kg (54 kJ/kg).
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p04] Research focuses on improving specific energy, reducing internal resistance, expanding temperature range, increasing lifetimes and reducing costs.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p04] Projects include tailored-pore-size electrodes, pseudocapacitive coating or doping materials and improved electrolytes.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p04] As of 2016 worldwide sales of supercapacitors is about US$400 million.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p04] The market for batteries (estimated by Frost & Sullivan) grew from US$47.5 billion, (76.4% or US$36.3 billion of which was rechargeable batteries) to US$95 billion.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p04] The market for supercapacitors is still a small niche market that is not keeping pace with its larger rival.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p04] In 2016, IDTechEx forecast sales to grow from $240 million to $2 billion by 2026, an annual increase of about 24%.
[src:supercapacitors/supercapacitor-p04] Supercapacitor costs in 2006 were US$0.01 per farad or US$2.85 per kilojoule, moving in 2008 below US$0.01 per farad, and were expected to drop further in the medium term.
